definition.value: Any structural anomaly of the ulna, a bone of the forearm the extends from the elbow to the little finger.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of folate in the blood circulation.

Folate is an essential water-soluble vitamin (vitamin B9) that is found in green leafy vegetables, cereals, legumes, and fruit. As a major methyl group donor, it plays an important role in one-carbon metabolism and is involved in DNA, RNA, and protein synthesis, in addition to its significant role in energy production and normal cell division. Low blood folate concentration is associated with an increased risk for neural tube defects during pregnancy.
Any abnormality in the total number of lymphocytes in the blood.

In human peripheral blood, five NK cell subpopulations can be defined on the basis of the relative expression of the markers CD16 and CD56: (1) CD56bright CD16- (50-70% of CD56bright), (2) CD56bright CD16dim (30-50% of CD56bright), (3) CD56dim CD16-, (4) CD56dim CD16bright, and (5) CD56- CD16bright. In healthy individuals, populations (3) and (5) are numerically in the minority.
Any structural abnormality of the tympanic membrane
The tympanic membrane is considered to be the border of middle and outer ear.
An abnormality of the composition of sweat or the levels of its components.
The concentration of iron in the blood circulation is outside the limits of normal.

Ferritin is an iron storage protein present in all cells of the organism. A small amount is found in plasma and serum, which is a reflection of iron stores in healthy individuals. A low serum ferritin concentration is usually regarded as an indicator of iron depletion, although the interpretation of normal or high serum ferritin values is challenging in the presence of acute or chronic inflammatory processes, as ferritin is increased in iron overload states and inflammation.
An increased amount of carboxylic acid in the urine.

label.value: Abnormality of extrinsic muscle of tongue

definition.value: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a phospholipid in the blood circulation.

An abnormally increased head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart.

Although HC measures skull size, it typically also reflects overall brain volume and has been described as a widely used proxy of neural growth and brain size. Brain size outside of normal values is an important risk factor for cognitive and motor delay. Microcephaly at birth has been termed primary microcephaly and that acquired after birth is secondary microcephaly.
Recurrent abnormal consumption of food, liquids, or objects that could have negative consequences for the individual.
Abnormal concentration of neopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Increased concentration of neopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Decreased concentration of neopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Any deviation from the normal concentration of neopterin in the blood circulation.
Neopterin can be found to have abnormal level in blood, CSF, or urine.
Abnormal concentration of a pterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Pterin is a coenzyme that occurs in various forms, such as biopterin, folic acid, xanthopterin, or methanopterin.
Concentration of biopterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
